more or less this objective,

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:10.120
my opinion about what
makes Gorey so interesting.

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:13.990
One of the things that Gorey used

00:24:13.990 --> 00:24:18.480
to tell people whenever people
asked him what does any of it mean

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:20.000
and even the person who used

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.880
to ask this question was
Andreas Brown himself

00:24:22.880 --> 00:24:25.680
and Gorey would almost
always invariably say,

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:29.090
"What you see is what you get."

00:24:29.090 --> 00:24:35.410
And I think that answer more or
less just managed to push off a lot

00:24:35.410 --> 00:24:39.770 position:56%
of people but I think when you think
about what Gorey was talking about,

00:24:39.770 --> 00:24:45.030
what you see is what you get, what
you understand, you can take this

00:24:45.030 --> 00:24:48.070
as what you understand is
what you can read into it.

00:24:48.070 --> 00:24:51.430
He loved it when people
read into his work only

00:24:51.430 --> 00:24:55.040
because it showed how
engaged people were.

00:24:55.040 --> 00:25:00.290
He didn't divulge meanings
pretty much of any of his works.

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:03.120
He would say, "Read into it.

00:25:03.120 --> 00:25:06.570
I'm happy to take whatever
you feel like,

00:25:06.570 --> 00:25:09.200
whatever translation
you come up with."

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:13.560
But there are some things
that he really enjoyed.

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:17.000
What you're seeing here is
some of the, some old footage

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:20.030
of films of Louis Feuillade.

00:25:20.030 --> 00:25:23.390
This one happens to
be from "Fantomas."

00:25:23.390 --> 00:25:29.860
When Gorey was in Harvard
they used to watch and also

00:25:29.860 --> 00:25:33.590
in New York they would
look for performances.

00:25:33.590 --> 00:25:37.120
This is 100 years old.

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:40.380
Most of this was, this
particular one was done in 1914.

00:25:40.380 --> 00:25:46.760
It was a series of what's
called -- the French hated it.

00:25:46.760 --> 00:25:50.650
It wasn't supposedly the high
art of filmmaking so they had,

00:25:50.650 --> 00:25:54.470
I forgot the name they gave it
but it wasn't a complimentary one

00:25:54.470 --> 00:25:59.640
but Gorey truly found
something in it and I think

00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:05.300
in a way you can actually see
some of his style being used here.

00:26:05.300 --> 00:26:07.380
I mean this is truly
different than a lot

00:26:07.380 --> 00:26:11.690
of silent film movies
especially the setting, the stage.

00:26:11.690 --> 00:26:21.740
An analyst, a critic for film
had a wonderful interpretation

00:26:21.740 --> 00:26:23.950
about the Feuillade films.

00:26:23.950 --> 00:26:30.580 position:56%
These were films that were not of
course, popular because they were --

00:26:30.580 --> 00:26:34.030
the narration proved to
be somewhat deceptive.

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:38.190
Feuillade enjoyed leading
a narration

00:26:38.190 --> 00:26:41.260
that wasn't necessarily
showing on the screen

00:26:41.260 --> 00:26:44.210
so that oftentimes the
audience would have to come

00:26:44.210 --> 00:26:46.960
up with their own conclusion
at the end

00:26:46.960 --> 00:26:50.240
because it wasn't a
straightforward narration

00:26:50.240 --> 00:26:54.150
and I think Gorey really
picked up on that style

00:26:54.150 --> 00:27:00.630
of not knowing who's
telling the story

00:27:00.630 --> 00:27:02.810
and what is going to
happen at the end.

00:27:02.810 --> 00:27:05.140
It's not a very linear kind
of unless you watch it over

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:10.310
and over again you're not going to
know what's going to happen next.

00:27:10.310 --> 00:27:13.720
This is the original music
that came with these.

00:27:13.720 --> 00:27:15.020
It's very interesting.

00:27:15.020 --> 00:27:19.670
It's very surreal and the
colors were also intentional.

00:27:19.670 --> 00:27:23.590
Another favorite of Gorey's
was the "The Tale of Genji"

00:27:23.590 --> 00:27:31.930 position:56%
by Murasaki Shikibu and her thousand
year-old novel Gorey read and found,

00:27:31.930 --> 00:27:36.970
